Ask HN: Why do I get so much “Yeti Backpack Cooler” spam?
text:
Subject: You've been chosen

Body (in an image): You have been chose to participate in our loyalty program for free...

I've been seeing messages like this constantly make the inbox in Gmail over the last few months (even after reporting at least 3-4 of this exact type of message).

Shouldn't this be a relatively easy catch for the spam filters? Seems like it has a few features that would make it stand out:

- Low reputation domain (tudkkuyfylukf[.]ml)

- Sender name (YETI Backpack-Cooler) the same as previously reported spam messages

- Subject looks like many spam messages (that are caught in the filter)

- No body text in the email

Are these messages doing something particularly smart to evade the filters? What could be going on here?

Ask HN: Does AI progress also fill you with dread?
text:
I don't think I've felt hopeful a single time since I saw what ChatGPT was capable of. Make no mistake, I find the technology incredible and fascinating - it's a monumental achievement. I grew up dreaming that I'd get to see AGI, and I feel like now we're close, if not already there.

But when I think about the world that this tech is coming out to, whose hands it will end up in, and the rhetoric from those people (e.g. this Paul Graham tweet from a few days ago [0]), I'm filled with nothing but dread. I have essentially zero faith that this will lead to better outcomes for most people. Instead I expect a massive new consolidation of wealth, and a lot of new misery for many people put out of work by AI. Less work for humans should mean good news, but we haven't yet built a world that can safely handle that reduction in work humanely.

Do you feel the same way? I especially want to hear from you if you don't - I would be more than happy to be dissuaded from this frankly quite apocalyptic view.

[0]: https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=33879690

Show HN: Sms2img, an SMS Interface for Stable Diffusion
text:
Hi, I've been working on this on and off for a bit now. I have been working on a web app (still very pre-alpha and doesn't really work yet, but its at sms2img.com) - but the core SMS interface is up and running and is alive and well :)

Here is the description I posted in the original link: "If you text 8145594701, it will send back an image with the prompt you specified. Currently only US numbers can send/receive texts because Twilio. Sorry to the rest of the planet!

I think this will likely fall over but I figured this would be a cool little thing to demo. I removed the NSFW filter so be mindful of your prompts!"

I originally posted this (https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=32696866) when SD 1.4 had just been released, and it was a very clunky PoC running off of a Google Colab Pro notebook. Currently running off Genesis Cloud and spending a decent chunk of change to keep it running. I just upgraded the model being used from SD v1.4 to SD v2.1, and the upgrade is definitely an interesting sight to behold. If you would like early access to new features (such as img2img, coming next week) as well as unlimited (up to 2000 images a day) image generations, please consider upgrading on the sms2img.com page. Please use the same number as the one you are texting in from as I intend to use that as a verification method.

For now, it is still free to use, but in order to continue running this, I will need to get more serious about at least paying for the costs to host this. I will be limiting to 3 image generations per day for free users starting in the very near future. Thank you! Please enjoy :)

Unfortunately, I didn't get into the AI Grant batch but decided to continue working on it. Given the recent release of SD 2.1, I wanted to share it again!

I have currently working on monetizing this as it is not inexpensive to host, but wanted to showcase this again!

I will give a QR code to a customer, they will input information, this information will be stored in my database (let's say google sheets or somewhere) and I want to grant them access to the information they inputted and to change it if necessary.

The problem is that I will have multiple clients inputting data and I want to grant them access only to the data they inputted, so they will not be able to see the rest's information.

Hope you can help me.

Ask HN: What is your advice for someone trying to build a “Hacker News clone”
text:

would you encourage me to go with this Idea? or you have another suggestion? if yes, which database do you think a should use? a relational (I'm a bit comfortable with Postgres) or some non relational (MongoDB). also if I want to put this in a micro-services format, how do I split up my services (like submissions, profiles...) I am new to this. I'm asking about which database since the mentioned stack is terminated by my school, but not the database.

as I said, the purpose of this project is education purposes only (also to show off on my resume/portfolio).

Thanks in advance
